full_text: When multiple policy transactions are started and based on the same policy period, it may create a preemption situation. The first job that finishes preempts all other jobs, as the jobs that try to complete later do not have the changes made by the job that finishes first. We will walk through an example with a policy of your choice. From the policy file, Start a Policy Change. Go to PA Coverages. Change the Comprehensive Deductible from 1000 to 250. Click Save Draft to save the changes. Do not issue this policy change job, but go back to the same policy file. Start another policy change. Start another policy change. This warning does not indicate that a preemption will necessarily occur, or that it already occurred. Go to PA Coverages. Change the Comprehensive Deductible from 1000 to 500 this time. We will finish this policy change. Click Quote. Issue the policy change. Since this job finishes first, it preempts the other open policy change job. It offers a link to go to the unfinished policy job created earlier. The preemption warning message and the handle preemption button appear on every page of the open policy change. Go to Policy Review. Expand the tree structure on the Differences tab, which compares the current policy change job with the existing policy data that it is based on. As you can see, it displays the existing policy's comprehensive deductible as 1000, which is prior to the other issued policy change, so it is not based on the most up-to-date policy data. You must handle the preemption before you can continue the policy change process. On the Handle Preemptions page, it compares the existing policy that the current job is based on with the other policy change job that has completed earlier. Expand the tree structure. Review the data. There are several options here. The Apply All Changes button allows you to apply changes from the job that finishes first. The Withdraw button discards the current job. The Decide Later button saves the draft and returns to the Policy Review screen. Let's click Apply All Changes. It goes back to the Differences tab on Policy Review, which compares the data to the policy review. The Preemptions tab pairs the current policy change job with the existing policy data that it is based on. Expand the tree structure. After applying all changes, the existing policy has been updated to the most recent data. This is the end of the demonstration of preemption.
